'''Gabriel Bernal Vargas''' (5 February 1915 &ndash; 25 May 2010)<ref name=conacultagobmx052610/><ref name=googletranslateConacultagobmx052610/>  was a [[Mexico|Mexican]] [[Painting|painter]], [[artist]] and [[cartoonist]], whose [[comic strip]] ''[[La Familia Burr<U+00F3>n]]'' was created in 1937.<ref name=eluniversal052510/><ref name=googletranslateEluniversal052510/><ref name=laht052810/> This cartoon has been described as one of the most important in Mexican [[popular culture]].<ref name=conacultagobmx052610/><ref name=googletranslateConacultagobmx052610/> Vargas won Mexico's "Premio Nacional de Periodismo" (National Journalism Prize) in 1983 and the "Premio Nacional de Ciencias y Artes en el <U+00E1>rea de Tradiciones Populares" ([[Premio Nacional de Ciencias y Artes|National Sciences and Arts Prize]]) in 2003.<ref name=conacultagobmx052610/><ref name=googletranslateConacultagobmx052610/><ref name=foxnews052510>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2010/05/25/gabriel-vargas-creator-mexicos-beloved-la-familia-burron-comic-strip-dies/|title=Gabriel Vargas, creator of Mexico's beloved 'La Familia Burron' comic strip, dies at 95|date=25 May 2010|work=[[Fox News Channel]]|accessdate=27 May 2010}}</ref><ref name=eluniversal052510>{{cite news|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/683023.html|title=Muere el caricaturista Gabriel Vargas|date=25 de mayo de 2010|work=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=27 May 2010}}</ref><ref name=googletranslateEluniversal052510>{{cite news|url=http://translate.google.com/translate?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.eluniversal.com.mx%2Fnotas%2F683023.html&sl=es&tl=en&hl=&ie=UTF-8|title=Muere el caricaturista Gabriel Vargas|date=25 de mayo de 2010|work=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|language=English|accessdate=27 May 2010}}</ref><ref name=dailycartoonist052610>{{cite web|url=http://dailycartoonist.com/index.php/2010/05/26/mexicos-gabriel-vargas-dies-at-age-95/|title=Mexico<U+2019>s Gabriel Vargas dies at age 95|last=Gardner|first=Alan|date=26 May 2010|work=The Daily Cartoonist|publisher=dailycartoonist.com|accessdate=27 May 2010}}</ref>

==Early life and education==
Gabriel Vargas was born in [[Tulancingo|Tulancingo, Hidalgo]], on 5 February 1915 and had 11 siblings.<ref name=conacultagobmx052610/><ref name=googletranslateConacultagobmx052610/> His father was a [[merchant]] and died when Gabriel was four years old.<ref name=eluniversal052510/><ref name=googletranslateEluniversal052510/> In 1922, his mother, Josefina Bernal, moved the family to [[Mexico City]].<ref name=conacultagobmx052610/><ref name=googletranslateConacultagobmx052610/><ref name=eluniversal052510/><ref name=googletranslateEluniversal052510/> Around 1928, Vargas began work as a [[draftsman]] for the ''[[Exc<U+00E9>lsior]]'' newspaper and eventually became its chief drawer<ref name=conacultagobmx052610/><ref name=googletranslateConacultagobmx052610/><ref name=eluniversal052510/><ref name=googletranslateEluniversal052510/> by 1931 when he was [[sixteen]].<ref name=conacultagobmx052610/><ref name=googletranslateConacultagobmx052610/> Vargas won an art contest sponsored by ''Panamericana Editorial'' which led to him penning his first [[comic]], ''Los Superlocos'', whose main [[protagonist]]s became the [[Explanation|basis]] for ''La Familia Burr<U+00F3>n''.<ref name=conacultagobmx052610/><ref name=googletranslateConacultagobmx052610/><ref name=eluniversal052510/><ref name=googletranslateEluniversal052510/>

==La Familia Burr<U+00F3>n==
In 1937, Vargas began drawing ''La Familia Burr<U+00F3>n'' as a separate [[Panel (comics)|piece]] which documented parents, Regino Burr<U+00F3>n and Borola Tacuche de Burr<U+00F3>n, their two teenage children, Regino Burr<U+00F3>n and Foforito Cantarranas, who was adopted by the Burr<U+00F3>ns.<ref name=conacultagobmx052610/><ref name=googletranslateConacultagobmx052610/><ref name=eluniversal052510/><ref name=googletranslateEluniversal052510/><ref name=foxnews052510/><ref name=globedia092809>{{cite web|url=http://mx.globedia.com/caricaturas-mexicanas-familia-burron|title=Caricaturas mexicanas: la familia Burr<U+00F3>n|date=28 September 2009|work=Globedia|publisher=mx.globedia.com|language=Spanish|accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref><ref name=googletranslateGlobedia092809>{{cite web|url=http://translate.google.com/translate?u=http%3A%2F%2Fmx.globedia.com%2Fcaricaturas-mexicanas-familia-burron&sl=es&tl=en&hl=&ie=UTF-8|title=Caricaturas mexicanas: la familia Burr<U+00F3>n|date=September 28, 2009|work=Globedia|publisher=[[Google Translate]]|language=English|accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref><ref name=sepiensaorgmx>{{cite web|url=http://sepiensa.org.mx/contenidos/2005/burron/burron1.htm|title=La Familia Burr<U+00F3>n|last=L<U+00F3>pez-Portillo|first=Esther|work=Sepiensa.org.mx|publisher=sepiensa.org.mx|language=Spanish|accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref><ref name=googletranslateSepiensaorgmx>{{cite web|url=http://translate.google.com/translate?u=http%3A%2F%2Fsepiensa.org.mx%2Fcontenidos%2F2005%2Fburron%2Fburron1.htm&sl=es&tl=en&hl=&ie=UTF-8|title=La Familia Burr<U+00F3>n|last=L<U+00F3>pez-Portillo|first=Esther|work=Sepiensa.org.mx|publisher=[[Google Translate]]|accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref> ''La Familia Burr<U+00F3>n'' profiled a [[lower class]] family's daily [[comedic]] struggles in an [[Poverty|impoverished]] Mexican [[barrio]].<ref name=foxnews052510/><ref name=globedia092809/><ref name=googletranslateGlobedia092809/><ref name=sepiensaorgmx/><ref name=googletranslateSepiensaorgmx/> At the height of its popularity, the comic strip helped [[Newspaper circulation|circulation sales]] to reach 500,000 copies a week.<ref name=dailycartoonist052610/><ref name=sepiensaorgmx/><ref name=googletranslateSepiensaorgmx/> The comic was temorarily suspended but resumed in 1978.<ref name=sepiensaorgmx/><ref name=googletranslateSepiensaorgmx/>

==Later life and death==
In 2007, [[Carlos Monsiv<U+00E1>is]], who is a [[patron]] of the arts, opened the [[Museo de El Estanquillo]] with an exhibition of Vargas' ''La Familia Burr<U+00F3>n'' paintings with the artist in person.<ref name=procesomx052510>{{cite web|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/rv/modHome/detalleExclusiva/79706|title=Fallece Gabriel Vargas, creador de La Familia Burr<U+00F3>n|last=Amador|first=Judith|date=25 de mayo 2010|work [[Proceso]]|publisher=proceso.com.mx|language=Spanish|accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref><ref name=googletranslateprocesomx052510>{{cite web|url=http://translate.google.com/translate?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.proceso.com.mx%2Frv%2FmodHome%2FdetalleExclusiva%2F79706&sl=es&tl=en&hl=&ie=UTF-8|title=Fallece Gabriel Vargas, creador de La Familia Burr<U+00F3>n|last=Amador|first=Judith|date=25 de mayo 2010|work=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]|publisher=[[Google Translate]]|language=English|accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref> The Burr<U+00F3>n Family were represented in painted forms by Regino Burr<U+00F3>n and Borola Tacuche de Burr<U+00F3>n, Regino and Foforito.<ref name=procesomx052510/><ref name=googletranslateprocesomx052510/> Vargas sat [[paralyzed]] because of an [[Suffering|affiction]] he had suffered for the past twenty years.<ref name=procesomx052510/><ref name=googletranslateprocesomx052510/>

The [[National Council for Culture and Arts|Consejo Nacional para la Cultura y las Artes]] stated Vargas died on 25 May 2010 at his [[Mexico City]] home.<ref name=conacultagobmx052610/><ref name=googletranslateConacultagobmx052610/><ref name=foxnews052510/>  His health had declined in recent years but no cause of death was given.<ref name=conacultagobmx052610/><ref name=googletranslateConacultagobmx052610/><ref name=foxnews052510/> According to a statement released by this council, Vargas was "one of the greatest representatives of the golden age of Mexican comics" and an "undeniable reference point for the nation<U+2019>s popular culture".<ref name=dailycartoonist052610/>

